WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.583
(upbeat music)

00:00:11.090 --> 00:00:14.720
- Steady-state cardiovascular
exercise is not part

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:19.720
of the X3 program, and get a
lot of questions about that,

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:25.360
because cardio has been,
the go to type thing

00:00:25.550 --> 00:00:29.590
for weight loss for a long
time and we're gonna explain

00:00:29.590 --> 00:00:33.320
why that's not true and
it's terrible advice

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:38.320
and also those better ways
to get cardiovascular health,

00:00:38.940 --> 00:00:41.840
meaning the health of
your heart and your lungs.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:44.170
Now, I am gonna also say

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:46.880
that if you wanna be a
great distance runner,

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:50.740
you have to distance run,
because the body's gonna adapt

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:53.110
to the environment that you put it in.

00:00:53.110 --> 00:00:55.150
So you put it in an environment

00:00:55.150 --> 00:00:57.070
that has extremely heavy loading,

00:00:57.070 --> 00:00:59.810
even heavier with variable
resistance and weight training,

00:00:59.810 --> 00:01:00.940
it's gonna adapt to that

00:01:00.940 --> 00:01:02.650
and you can get bigger and stronger.

00:01:02.650 --> 00:01:05.850
If you put the body in an environment

00:01:05.850 --> 00:01:09.100
where it has to go long distances,

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:14.100
it's going to make changes,
based on optimizing you

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:16.150
for going long distances.

00:01:16.150 --> 00:01:17.640
And let me explain,

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:20.233
why that's not necessarily
a good or bad thing.

00:01:21.140 --> 00:01:22.750
It's just a thing.

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:24.300
And that's what the body does.

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:25.950
So, you got to think about

00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:28.770
what the central nervous
system is gonna do,

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:30.850
when you're trying to show the body

00:01:30.850 --> 00:01:33.520
that you wanna go long
distances, you know,

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:35.420
with a limited amount of fuel,

00:01:35.420 --> 00:01:37.390
'cause you're trying to
lose body fat, right?

00:01:37.390 --> 00:01:42.390
So what happens, is the body
sees an energy expenditure,

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:47.600
and a fuel availability that
don't necessarily match.

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:51.040
So, let's say you run 10
miles and you're running

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:54.040
for an extended period
of time, the body says,

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:59.040
okay, we want to shrink
the engine, of the body

00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:02.400
because then we'll burn less fuel

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:04.870
as we go that same distance.

00:02:04.870 --> 00:02:07.770
So you lose muscle when you do cardio,

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:09.850
and cortisol, attenuates this.

00:02:09.850 --> 00:02:14.240
So cortisol goes up, when
you do steady-state cardio

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:15.840
and you start to lose muscle.

00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:19.960
The other thing cardio does,
is it protects your body fat

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:22.650
and helps you store more body fat.

00:02:22.650 --> 00:02:24.960
So now, most people who do cardio

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:26.400
are also at a caloric deficit,

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:30.380
so they're not necessarily in
a danger of getting fatter,

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:32.950
but they have a hormonal situation

00:02:32.950 --> 00:02:35.330
that is protecting their body fat

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:37.440
and sacrificing their muscle.

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:40.270
So the weight you lose when you do cardio,

00:02:40.270 --> 00:02:41.550
is muscle not body fat.

00:02:41.550 --> 00:02:44.470
It's the opposite of what almost everybody

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:47.160
who does cardio wants.

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:49.460
So, this is why it's
not part of the program

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:51.580
and there's studies that back this up,

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:53.470
this has been very well understood.

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:56.360
This has been in literature
and academic literature

00:02:56.360 --> 00:02:57.870
for more than 40 years.

00:02:57.870 --> 00:03:00.870
The fact that the fitness
industry, never picked it up

00:03:00.870 --> 00:03:03.440
is just shame on the fitness industry.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:06.130
It's a, there's not a lot of people

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:11.110
who can read a lot of research
in the fitness industry.

00:03:11.110 --> 00:03:14.390
So, I understand why, but you know,

00:03:14.390 --> 00:03:18.120
I go to scientific conferences
on sports medicine,

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:23.020
and they talk about this all
the time, whereas you look

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:26.330
at the industry and it's
like, cardio's for weight loss

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:28.910
and strength training
is for building muscle

00:03:28.910 --> 00:03:31.910
and neither story is even
close to being that simple

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:34.140
and one of those stories is dead wrong.

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:37.490
Now there's another great
study, that's a meta analysis

00:03:37.490 --> 00:03:41.730
that looks at how strength
training actually makes

00:03:41.730 --> 00:03:46.730
your heart and lungs, stronger
than cardiovascular exercise.

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:49.020
So the point is health.

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:51.270
You're getting everything you
need from strength training

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:54.180
and X3 is strength
training, so you will get

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:59.180
that cardiovascular health
benefit from your X3 exercise

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:03.800
as you would from strength
training, probably even

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:07.850
to a higher degree and
more so, than you would get

00:04:07.850 --> 00:04:10.029
from cardiovascular exercise.

00:04:10.029 --> 00:04:12.760
So, we've got the health thing covered

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:17.103
and you're gonna be leaner
and stronger and look better.

00:04:18.030 --> 00:04:20.810
Women will look, you know,
in a more feminine shape

00:04:20.810 --> 00:04:23.520
with a little bit of
muscle and less body fat,

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:25.900
and man obviously have the hormones

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:27.250
to build a lot more muscle.

00:04:27.250 --> 00:04:31.870
That is why, we do not include
cardiovascular exercise

00:04:31.870 --> 00:04:33.360
in our programming.

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:37.110
Lastly, I'd like to add, I know
there's gonna be some people

00:04:37.110 --> 00:04:42.110
who do cardio, steady-state
cardio, maybe triathletes,

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:47.377
maybe distance runners, they
can check out, the book,

00:04:47.377 --> 00:04:49.700
"Weightlifting is a Waste of Time" where

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:53.630
they can see the indepth analysis

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:55.730
and all of the references on this subject

00:04:55.730 --> 00:04:58.583
because we covered it,
in the book, at length.

